  "why": "RobOT enforces similarity constraints (an ε-ball) and uses distance checks during each fuzzing step, and it maintains/extends seeds by appending successful mutants for further mutation — i.e., similarity is controlled relative to the current (most recent) seed during each mutation iteration but the paper does not enforce or check similarity back to the original seed to prevent cumulative drift. The approach therefore enforces semantic/naturalness constraints between successive mutation steps only, without accounting for possible accumulation of distortions across multiple iterations.",
  "evidence": "III-C Robustness-Oriented Testing Metrics (page 304): \"we assume that a test case x* is generated in the neighborhood e—ball around x0, i.e., {x | ||x - x0||_p < e}.\" (definition of the ε-ball neighborhood used for mutations). III-C Zero-Order Loss (page 304): \"ZOL(x*, f) = J(f(θ, x*), y), where y is the ground-truth label of x.\" (shows the oracle assumes semantic equivalence within the neighborhood). III-E FOL Guided Fuzzing / Algorithm 3 (page 305): \"Maintain a list s_list = [seed]\"; \"Let x' = x\"; \"... Let dis = Dist(x', x) ... if FOL(x') > FOLm and dis < e then FOLm = FOL(x'); s_list.append(x') ...\" and \"if FOL(x') < ε and dis < e then s_list.append(x') ...\" (demonstrates distance is checked relative to the current seed x and mutants x' are appended to the seed list for further mutation). These excerpts indicate per-step (successive) distance enforcement within an ε-ball but no mechanism is shown that constrains cumulative distance relative to the original seed across multiple iterative mutations."
